body:
This behavior does not surprise me: You're using the same instance of `DemoApplicationTests` and call `beforeEach()`, `parallel()`, and `afterEach()` from different threads. When one of the threads prints in `afterEach()`, another thread is very likely to have already called `beforeEach()` or `parallel()` which modifies the test instance.

Since issues like this one are inevitable when using `@TestInstance(PER_CLASS)`, I think we should change the default execution mode to `SAME_THREAD` in this case.

@junit-team/junit-lambda Thoughts?

The following simplified example demonstrates the same behavior without Spring Boot in the picture.

```java
@TestInstance(PER_CLASS)
class DemoApplicationTests {

	Klass klass;

	@BeforeEach
	void beforeEach() {
		klass = new Klass(Thread.currentThread().getName());
	}

	@RepeatedTest(8)
	void parallel() {
		klass.setField("Modified: " + klass.getField());
	}

	@AfterEach
	void afterEach() {
		System.out.println(String.format("%s - %s", Thread.currentThread().getName(), klass.getField()));
	}

}
```

Without a change in JUnit itself, you have two options for avoiding the undesired behavior.

### Disable Parallel Execution

```java
@TestInstance(PER_CLASS)
@Execution(SAME_THREAD)
class DemoApplicationTests {

	Klass klass;

	@BeforeEach
	void beforeEach() {
		klass = new Klass(Thread.currentThread().getName());
	}

	@RepeatedTest(8)
	void parallel() {
		klass.setField("Modified: " + klass.getField());
	}

	@AfterEach
	void afterEach() {
		System.out.println(String.format("%s - %s", Thread.currentThread().getName(), klass.getField()));
	}

}
```

### Store test instance state in a `ThreadLocal`

```java
@TestInstance(PER_CLASS)
class DemoApplicationTests {

	ThreadLocal<Klass> klass = new ThreadLocal<>();

	@BeforeEach
	void beforeEach() {
		klass.set(new Klass(Thread.currentThread().getName()));
	}

	@RepeatedTest(8)
	void parallel() {
		klass.get().setField("Modified: " + klass.get().getField());
	}

	@AfterEach
	void afterEach() {
		System.out.println(String.format("%s - %s", Thread.currentThread().getName(), klass.get().getField()));
	}

}
```

The first option completely disables parallel execution, thereby avoiding the undesired behavior completely but obviously executing each test sequentially.

```
ForkJoinPool-1-worker-1 - Modified: ForkJoinPool-1-worker-1
ForkJoinPool-1-worker-1 - Modified: ForkJoinPool-1-worker-1
ForkJoinPool-1-worker-1 - Modified: ForkJoinPool-1-worker-1
ForkJoinPool-1-worker-1 - Modified: ForkJoinPool-1-worker-1
ForkJoinPool-1-worker-1 - Modified: ForkJoinPool-1-worker-1
ForkJoinPool-1-worker-1 - Modified: ForkJoinPool-1-worker-1
ForkJoinPool-1-worker-1 - Modified: ForkJoinPool-1-worker-1
ForkJoinPool-1-worker-1 - Modified: ForkJoinPool-1-worker-1
```

The second option allows the tests to continue to execute in parallel but introduces more work for the author of the test.

```
ForkJoinPool-1-worker-3 - Modified: ForkJoinPool-1-worker-3
ForkJoinPool-1-worker-4 - Modified: ForkJoinPool-1-worker-4
ForkJoinPool-1-worker-2 - Modified: ForkJoinPool-1-worker-2
ForkJoinPool-1-worker-4 - Modified: ForkJoinPool-1-worker-4
ForkJoinPool-1-worker-2 - Modified: ForkJoinPool-1-worker-2
ForkJoinPool-1-worker-3 - Modified: ForkJoinPool-1-worker-3
ForkJoinPool-1-worker-2 - Modified: ForkJoinPool-1-worker-2
ForkJoinPool-1-worker-2 - Modified: ForkJoinPool-1-worker-2
```
